net.automatalib.commons.util.array

Class RichArray<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • net.automatalib.commons.util.array.RichArray<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - element type
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, Cloneable, Iterable<T>, Collection<T>, IntFunction<T>, List<T>, RandomAccess

    public class RichArray<T>
extends Object
implements List<T>, IntFunction<T>, RandomAccess, Serializable, Cloneable
    A "modern", object-oriented wrapper for plain Java arrays.

    Instances of this class are backed by a plain Java array. The reference to this array never changes. It is impossible to obtain an outside reference to the backing array; however, if an array is supplied to a constructor of this class, all methods of this class manipulate the original array.

    This class was designed for efficiency. The many methods it offers are intended to allow direct manipulation of the backing array as often as possible, eliminating the indirection via get(int) and update(int, Object) methods.

    This class is designed to "feel" like an array as much as possible. This includes:

    • its length (or size) is fixed and cannot be changed once created
    • the length is accessible via a public final field length
    • it is (shallow) cloneable
    On the other hand, it implements the List interface. Note, however, that none of the optional methods are implemented.
    Author:
    Malte Isberner
